eering model for studying public writing in other societies and offer powerful evidence to show that writing is a highly charged and deeply embedded social practice.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGeneral. 4aLanguage Arts & Disciplines. 4aLinguistics. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aBierman, Irene A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020802540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091878840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520918788423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520918788/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles